result.execSummary:
The defendant Jason W Kasten was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Identity Theft - Obtain Money or Credit [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.203(2)(a).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Petition and Stipulation to Waive Appearance and Hearing

10:59am Court in session
Defendant Jason W Kasten appeared, Samuel Thomas Berg appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Agent Deanna Weber appears in person. 

Matter before the Court is a probation review hearing, Deft was extended a year ago to pay restitution, Deft due to discharge in Oct. 
Record by Agent Weber as to payments made so far. $2205.00 is still owed to victim, per Agent Weber.
State is in compliance with Ch. 950

Court inquires if Deft has a plan to pay off the balance so that he can be discharged, response by Deft. 
State makes record that Deft has paid $1450 in the last year, which is $27/week. State is asking that probation be extended for 12 months.
Record by Agent Weber as to decision at the prior probation review hearing. 

Court has colloquy with Deft, Deft responds to Court's questions. 
At last hearing, Court made record that if Deft paid $50/week for the last 12 months that the remaining balance would be converted to civil judgment & Deft could be discharged. 

Agent Weber believes Deft has made a good-faith effort, her records indicate that Deft has paid $1900 since last hearing.
Record by ADA Berg

Court makes record that if Deft can pay $700 by Oct. 18th, 2021, which will mean the Deft paid $2600.00 in the last year, Court will allow Deft to discharge, if Deft does not pay $700 by Oct. 18, 2021, then probation will extend 12 months or until the balance is paid.

11:09am Court in recess
Probation review hearing on September 9, 2021 at 11:00 am.

records.addlTxt: Petition and Stipulation to Waive Appearance and Hearing

09:36 AM PROBATION REVIEW HEARING:  Defendant Jason W Kasten appeared, ADA Matthew R. Leusink appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Probation Agent Deanna Weber appears on behalf of DOC.  There is a request for Judgment on the unpaid restitution.  Atty Leusink makes record as to the State's concerns.  It appears that the restitution amount is the same.  Agent Weber says this is deft's 2nd extension.  When working, they did have a wage assignment.  Deft was in jail for quite a bit of the first term of his probation.  He then got an extension.  Agent Weber makes record as to his employment history - didn't have transportation - lost his housing - then COVID came.  He is not working at Generac in Whitewater.  Majority of his money goes towards child support. Agent says he is a hard worker.  His last payment on this was over a year ago.  Court asks why he hasn't paid at least something.  Response by Deft as to currently hourly wage.  He gets paid every week.  He says he can afford about $50 every week.  Court will extend 1 year.  Deft to pay $50 per week for the next year and Court will find a good fair effort.  Response by Atty Leusink.  Court orders probation extended for 1 full year - to pay $50 per week starting October 8th.  Probation extended to 10/18/2021 unless restitution is paid completely by that date.  9:44 am  Court in recess.
